BaghdadI strongly appraise such initiatives.But it sounds to me that this symposium was only organized for foreign reporters and it lackeda voice of a local reporter.Iraqi reporters, for example and I think this is the case in all conflict areas, have been bearing huge responsibility since late 2004 when it became dangerous for foreign reporters to go out.Theyworked as reporters, translators, news gatherers and fixers etc... and faced different kinds of threats.The important thing is not only how to protect these local reporters from security threats but also how to maintain their rights as the majority of them have been working since 2003 without written contracts that preserve their rights.Some of them got killed and others maimed or handicapped as a result to their work but their families didn't get any compensation.The majority of the Iraq reporters are being laid off by their employers, who are not interested in Iraq's story anymore, without getting appropriate end-of-service bonus.So I really advise to consider a place for the local reporters in the set of the security protocol.Good luck!
