nment and the Western-backed opposition, U.N. envoy Lakhdar Brahimi announced that the two sides had agreed to meet in the same room. Hari Sreenivasan reports on the small steps of progress at the Syrian peace talks in Geneva. Continue reading →RELATEDTalks between Syrian government, opposition back on despite tense day in GenevaSyrian govt., opposition offer more heated rhetoric ahead of mediated meetingJanuary 23, 2014 Though open talks took a break for a day, U.N. Special Envoy to Syria Lakhdar Brahimi met separately with the Syrian government’s delegation and the opposition, ahead of a planned, mediated meeting between the two sides. Hari Sreenivasan gets an update from chief foreign correspondent Margaret Warner, reporting from Geneva. Continue reading →Peace talks open with disagreement over Assad’s future in SyriaJanuary 22, 2014 Infighting and acrimony marked the first day of talks on the Syrian war. While State Secretary Kerry and other officials insisted that a transitional government could not include current President Bashar al-Assad, the Syrian foreign minister insisted no country but Syria could dictate its own future. Margaret Warner reports. Continue reading →Ban Ki-moon closes Syrian peace talksJanuary 22, 2014 BY newsdesk United Nation’s Ban Ki-moon called for the Syrian delegations, representing the government and opposition party, to work towards a solution to the three-year civil war. Continue reading →UPDATE: Ban Ki-Moon invites Iran to the Syria peace talks, Margaret Warner is thereJanuary 20, 2014 The Wall Street Journal reports the U.S. expects the UN to revoke their invitation to Iran to attend the Syria peace talks in Geneva. Continue reading →Israeli Defense Minister offers harsh words for Kerry’s peace planJanuary 14, 2014 BY Andy Swab Israel’s Defense Minister Moshe Ya’alon vocally criticized U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry’s recent peace initiative between Israel and the Palestinian Territories. Continue reading →PHOTO: Potato diplo